Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.230 --> 00:00:01.563
MALE SPEAKER: Welcome, everyone.

00:00:01.563 --> 00:00:03.820
It's my pleasure to
welcome all of you

00:00:03.820 --> 00:00:06.810
to Professor David
Patterson's talk.

00:00:06.810 --> 00:00:09.690
David Patterson probably
needs no introduction.

00:00:09.690 --> 00:00:11.500
He's been a professor
of computer science

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:15.630
at University of California,
Berkeley for 40 years now.

00:00:15.630 --> 00:00:18.620
And he's made a lot of
pioneering contributions

00:00:18.620 --> 00:00:21.580
in computer systems, a lot
of which are technologies

00:00:21.580 --> 00:00:22.990
we use at Google and elsewhere.

00:00:22.990 --> 00:00:25.990
So RISC, reduced
instruction set computers,

00:00:25.990 --> 00:00:29.260
RAID, Network of
Workstations, and a lot more.

00:00:29.260 --> 00:00:31.180
He has a pretty long bio here.

00:00:31.180 --> 00:00:33.650
I didn't realize he
has won 35 awards.

00:00:33.650 --> 00:00:36.497
And all of them are
pretty prestigious.

00:00:36.497 --> 00:00:39.080
National Academy of Engineering,
National Academy of Sciences,

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:41.885
Silicon Valley
Engineering Hall of Fame,

00:00:41.885 --> 00:00:43.280
IEEE [INAUDIBLE] medal.

00:00:43.280 --> 00:00:45.870
And I'm sure I'm offending
some significant award by not

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.600
saying that, but he's had a
very distinguished career.

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:51.950
And this talk today,
in his own words,

00:00:51.950 --> 00:00:53.560
collects advice that
I wish I had been

00:00:53.560 --> 00:00:55.260
given when I started my career.

00:00:55.260 --> 00:00:57.280
And given how
distinguished that's been,

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:00.200
I think it's a talk we are
ail going to benefit from.

00:01:00.200 --> 00:01:00.890
So, welcome.

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:02.780
DAVID PATTERSON:
Well, this is-- what

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:08.009
happened is I decided-- somebody
wrote me these slides are

00:01:08.009 --> 00:01:09.300
about how to have a bad career.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:10.120
I've been out there
for a long time.

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:12.450
And they asked me if
there was a video of it.

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:13.850
And I couldn't find one.

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:16.510
I actually figured out that
I gave this talk first 20

00:01:16.510 --> 00:01:18.640
years ago, but I've
given it over the years.

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:21.140
So I decided to
record it at Berkeley.

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:23.510
And it ended up-- and
I announced my plans

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:25.810
to retire two days before this.

00:01:25.810 --> 00:01:28.440
So it got a lot of visibility.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:29.890
And it's fun to come here.

00:01:29.890 --> 00:01:32.900
As far as I can tell, all
of my-- oh, yeah, sorry.

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.560
As far as I can tell,
all of my former students

00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:40.090
are going to end
up here some time.

00:01:40.090 --> 00:01:41.590
Also, I have to ask
them, if they're

00:01:41.590 --> 00:01:42.779
leaving, where they are.

00:01:42.779 --> 00:01:44.070
I know where they're ending up.

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:47.040
And so it feels like
it's a home week here.

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:48.590
As I said, this is
the advice I wish

00:01:48.590 --> 00:01:52.310
I would've had in my career.

00:01:52.310 --> 00:01:56.385
This got started
about 30 years ago.

00:01:56.385 --> 00:01:58.260
I decided I wanted to
give advice on talks.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:00.637
So I wrote, "How to
Give a Bad Talk."

00:02:00.637 --> 00:02:01.720
And that was a lot of fun.

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:04.320
And about 10 years later,
"How to Have a Bad Career."

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.140
And about a couple
years ago, I did "How

00:02:07.140 --> 00:02:08.889
to Have a Bad Research Center."

00:02:08.889 --> 00:02:12.050
So this is my bad series.

00:02:12.050 --> 00:02:16.265
Now I'm just going to put
the-- if you're interested,

00:02:16.265 --> 00:02:18.640
these slides are certainly
available as well as the talk.

00:02:18.640 --> 00:02:21.560
And there's a lot
of papers and things

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:23.860
that you can cite if you
want to read more about it.

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:27.100
And I'd like to thank a bunch
of people for making suggestions

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:29.610
that I've incorporated, or
their careers inspired them.

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:31.890
One of those two.

00:02:31.890 --> 00:02:36.746
So the parts-- there's two parts
to the talk, the kind of tongue

00:02:36.746 --> 00:02:38.120
in cheek how to
have a bad career

00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:39.590
and then how to
avoid a bad career.

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:41.810
And then I'll open up for
questions and answers,

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:44.040
and then I'll wrap
things up whenever

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:46.530
we have to wrap things up
and take the last 5 or 10

00:02:46.530 --> 00:02:49.680
minutes talking about my
story, how I got here,

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:51.030
and what works for me.

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:55.210
So you want to be a
leader of the field,

00:02:55.210 --> 00:02:56.790
especially if
you're in academia.

00:02:56.790 --> 00:02:57.960
So how can you do that?

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:01.540
Well, invent a new field is
a really good way to do that.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.750
And you want to be the
only person in that field.

00:03:03.750 --> 00:03:07.910
So how can you invent a field
and then be the only person?

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:10.829
Well, one way is, different
from other fields,

00:03:10.829 --> 00:03:12.120
you want to be the lone ranger.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:13.661
And a way you can
be the lone ranger,

00:03:13.661 --> 00:03:18.620
the only one who is there,
is your personality can help.

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:22.660
If you adopt the Prima Donna
personality-- and some people

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:24.390
don't know what
a Prima Donna is.

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:25.990
But if you adopt
that personality,

00:03:25.990 --> 00:03:27.460
nobody will want
to work with you,

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:28.750
and you can drive people away.

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:30.624
And then you'll be the
world's leading expert

00:03:30.624 --> 00:03:32.750
because you're the
only one in that field.

00:03:32.750 --> 00:03:35.090
In terms of the research
horizons for your new field,

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:39.940
you want to have a lot of
flexibility on success.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.420
You don't want to get too far.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.640
And if you say
it's 20 years out,

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:47.430
then you've got 19 safe years.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:50.350
And nobody's going to accuse
you of doing engineering

00:03:50.350 --> 00:03:53.590
work if it's 20 years out.

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:56.210
And stick to that topic
for your whole career.

00:03:56.210 --> 00:03:57.930
Now if I'd only
followed that advice--

00:03:57.930 --> 00:04:00.890
my dissertation was
on micro-programming.

00:04:00.890 --> 00:04:02.790
If I had stuck to this,
I would absolutely

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:04.540
be the world's expert
on micro-programming

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:06.831
partly because no one's built
a computer with microcode

00:04:06.831 --> 00:04:08.890
in 25 years.

00:04:08.890 --> 00:04:11.720
And you kind of think of
it like it's like fashion.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:13.590
Skinny jeans are popular now.

00:04:13.590 --> 00:04:15.050
They were popular 25 years ago.

00:04:15.050 --> 00:04:17.466
If you had just kept them, you
could reuse your old jeans.

00:04:17.466 --> 00:04:18.540
So research is like that.

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:19.410
Wait.

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:22.240
It'll come back to you.

00:04:22.240 --> 00:04:23.370
OK.

00:04:23.370 --> 00:04:25.790
Let complexity be your guide.

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:27.310
Confuse thine enemies.

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:29.400
The best thing you can
say, it's so complicated.

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:32.460
I can't understand what
you're talking about.

00:04:32.460 --> 00:04:34.770
You've done a good job.

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:36.979
One reason is it's easier
to claim credit for things.

00:04:36.979 --> 00:04:38.478
If somebody else
has done some work,

00:04:38.478 --> 00:04:40.220
you can say, well,
that was in my paper.

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:41.678
And since they
don't understand it,

00:04:41.678 --> 00:04:45.110
how can they contradict you?

00:04:45.110 --> 00:04:47.680
The other thing that's
surprising-- it's

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:49.860
really a lot easier
to be complicated.

00:04:49.860 --> 00:04:52.770
You read the first end
papers, and then you

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:53.770
figure out the next one.

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:54.550
And people publish it.

00:04:54.550 --> 00:04:57.110
It's really much harder to be
simple than to be complicated.

00:04:57.110 --> 00:04:59.050
So that's the easy way to do it.

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:01.274
And this sentence
captures it, right?

00:05:01.274 --> 00:05:03.440
If it's unsimple, how could
distinguished colleagues

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:05.250
in departments around the
world be possibly appreciative

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:06.140
and so on and so on?

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:06.681
There you go.

00:05:06.681 --> 00:05:09.540
That's the way to
speak and to talk.

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:10.840
Never be proven wrong.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:13.610
The first thing you want to do
is don't implement anything.

00:05:13.610 --> 00:05:16.070
It's hard to prove you wrong
if you don't implement it.

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:19.130
Now if some out of control
colleague builds something,

00:05:19.130 --> 00:05:22.740
then whatever you do, don't run
any quantitative experiments.

00:05:22.740 --> 00:05:28.100
If they're not quantitative,
then you can't be proven wrong.

00:05:28.100 --> 00:05:29.519
You've got the intuition.

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:31.560
You can just kind of
extrapolate with the results

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:34.340
that there are, put that
in without any experience.

00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:36.870
And your job isn't
to help the critics.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:39.100
That's their job to figure out.

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:40.080
Don't help them out.

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:43.180
Now another reason
is that clearly

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:45.790
the success of the career is
to publish as much as you can.

00:05:45.790 --> 00:05:48.810
And it takes time to
build and to measure.

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:51.020
So if you don't do that,
you can get more results

00:05:51.020 --> 00:05:53.507
and have a more
successful career.

00:05:53.507 --> 00:05:55.590
If somebody does it, the
last thing you want to do

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:57.756
is run any benchmarks,
because then they can compare

00:05:57.756 --> 00:06:00.010
your results to other things.

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:07.680
The advice being that
you've got those safe years.

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:11.930
And the benchmarks
can just-- the way you

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:14.170
get out of that is to
say, well, this computer

00:06:14.170 --> 00:06:18.350
is for future programs,
not for current programs.

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:20.110
And then these
benchmarks are too

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:22.337
antiquated to run
on my computer.

00:06:22.337 --> 00:06:24.420
Now the other thing that
we do in computer science

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:26.650
is we reject all the past.

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:27.400
We're a new field.

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:28.858
We're both science
and engineering.

00:06:28.858 --> 00:06:31.310
So we're not hide bound
by old fashioned things

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:32.760
like the scientific method.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:35.250
We have the computer
scientific method.

00:06:35.250 --> 00:06:41.320
Instead of a hypothesis,
we have a hunch.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:42.840
A sequence of experiments.

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:46.010
We know that sequential is slow.

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:49.696
So what we do-- we
change one experiment,

00:06:49.696 --> 00:06:50.820
all the parameters at once.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.860
That's much faster than
the sequential approach.

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:54.560
Parallelism is a good idea.

00:06:54.560 --> 00:06:58.240
And rather than prove or
disprove our hypothesis,

00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:01.575
we discard if it doesn't
support the hunch.

00:07:01.575 --> 00:07:02.450
There's lots of data.

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:03.227
It's a big data.

00:07:03.227 --> 00:07:04.060
Throw away the data.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:05.476
There's still
plenty of data left.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:09.664
And document for
others to reproduce?

00:07:09.664 --> 00:07:10.580
We've already done it.

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:12.130
We'll have more
results of the field

00:07:12.130 --> 00:07:13.970
if we don't waste our
time trying to reproduce

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:14.845
each other's results.

00:07:14.845 --> 00:07:17.390
That's the computer
scientific method.

00:07:17.390 --> 00:07:18.730
Don't be distracted by others.

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:21.450
Avoid feedback.

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:23.869
A big part of that
is conversation.

00:07:23.869 --> 00:07:25.410
And if you don't
say anything, people

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:26.826
might think you're
not very smart.

00:07:26.826 --> 00:07:29.850
So the corollary of that
is loud is smart, OK?

00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:32.573
So be loud in conversations,
even when you don't

00:07:32.573 --> 00:07:34.000
know what you're talking about.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.310
People will think you know
what you're talking about.

00:07:39.269 --> 00:07:40.810
If you're the world's
leading expert,

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:43.060
you don't really need
to read other things,

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:46.120
because you're
the expert, right?

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.240
And you don't have to interact
with others because they're not

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:51.670
as good as you are.

00:07:51.670 --> 00:07:53.640
In terms of doing
reviews for paper,

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:58.850
if it's simple and obvious,
insult the prior authors.

00:07:58.850 --> 00:08:00.780
If you accepted something
simple and obvious,

00:08:00.780 --> 00:08:04.330
they probably thought of
it, so you should reject it.

00:08:04.330 --> 00:08:07.030
If they're quantitative
results-- and I've

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:08.620
gotten this review before.

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:09.770
Well, I already knew that.

00:08:09.770 --> 00:08:12.050
So there's no
surprise to reject it.

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:16.460
And everything else, you
might as well just reject.

00:08:16.460 --> 00:08:18.620
They're kind of competitors
to you in some way.

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:21.450
And if their paper doesn't
get published, then you win.

00:08:21.450 --> 00:08:23.830
So that's a good guideline.

00:08:23.830 --> 00:08:26.075
Now, publishing journals
is technology transfer.

00:08:26.075 --> 00:08:27.700
You're the leading
person in the world.

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:28.270
You're the expert.

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:29.978
All you have to do is
write in a journal.

00:08:29.978 --> 00:08:33.460
It's not your job to make
it understandable to others,

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.090
to the ordinary engineers.

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:38.320
Going to conferences just wastes
some of your valuable time

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:40.500
that you could be coming
up with new ideas.

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.929
And having to interact
with industry and things

00:08:43.929 --> 00:08:45.360
like that-- that's
a time waster.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:46.860
You write the journals.

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:48.430
You're done.

00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:51.519
Now clearly, the winner is
the one with the most papers

00:08:51.519 --> 00:08:52.560
at the end of the career.

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:54.870
So I've come up with
this pyramid of success

00:08:54.870 --> 00:08:55.660
for publication.

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:58.180
It follows the rule of four.

00:08:58.180 --> 00:09:00.930
And the guideline is the
LPU, least publishable unit--

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:02.160
the LPU is good for you.

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:03.482
So you start off with one idea.

00:09:03.482 --> 00:09:05.940
Then with the rule of four,
you get four journal papers out

00:09:05.940 --> 00:09:07.140
of that.

00:09:07.140 --> 00:09:08.700
With the miracle of
world processing,

00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:10.880
then you can get 16
extended abstracts

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:13.890
and 64 technical reports
from one single idea.

00:09:13.890 --> 00:09:16.860
That's 84 publications
gets that.

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:19.430
And then in terms of
getting credit for it,

00:09:19.430 --> 00:09:22.450
my advice is to change your
name to the Swedish spelling

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:24.020
of Anderson.

00:09:24.020 --> 00:09:27.142
And then there's
the awkward time.

00:09:27.142 --> 00:09:29.350
Oh, how are we going to put
the authors on the table?

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:33.750
You'll just say, well, I've
always done it alphabetically.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:35.920
All my papers [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:36.630
All right.

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:40.330
Writing commandments
for a bad career.

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:41.950
Thou shalt not define terms.

00:09:41.950 --> 00:09:43.900
That's what
dictionaries are for.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:46.310
And explaining things-- that'll
just insult the readers.

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:50.980
So you want to be a little
bit more mysterious than that.

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:56.340
Thou shalt replace I will
build with I have been built.

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:59.094
Probably by the time your paper
gets published in a journal,

00:09:59.094 --> 00:10:00.510
somebody will have
implemented it.

00:10:00.510 --> 00:10:04.060
So it's OK to do that.

00:10:04.060 --> 00:10:07.190
Thou shalt not mention
drawbacks to your report.

00:10:07.190 --> 00:10:08.430
That's not your job.

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:11.410
That's the job of the critics
to figure out the drawbacks.

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:14.290
If you hide that,
they'll never notice it.

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:17.380
Thou shalt not reference
any papers, again,

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:19.860
except for maybe your own
or at your institution.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:22.350
And if the papers
were any good, they'd

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:23.780
be people at your institution.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:25.102
So don't do that.

00:10:25.102 --> 00:10:27.060
And then you should
publish before implementing

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:29.018
because that's when your
system is the fastest.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:32.402
OK.

00:10:32.402 --> 00:10:33.860
Talk commandments
for a bad career.

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:37.280
This is my bad career talk.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:39.030
Thou shalt not be neat.

00:10:39.030 --> 00:10:42.200
Why take the time to
spend it on your slides

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:45.330
to fix spelling errors,
grammatical errors?

00:10:45.330 --> 00:10:49.410
You've can spend that
time on research.

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:50.990
Thou shalt not waste space.

00:10:50.990 --> 00:10:52.380
You use up a lot of slides.

00:10:52.380 --> 00:10:54.420
That's a lot of kilobytes
being wasted there.

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.280
You can save, like,
100 kilobytes a year,

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:57.260
which saves some money.

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:01.040
Thou shalt not covet brevity.

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:04.360
Do you really want to
sustain the stereotype

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:05.810
that engineers can't write?

00:11:05.810 --> 00:11:10.490
You want to show full
paragraphs, beautiful English,

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:12.690
and read it aloud.

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:14.150
Thou shalt cover
thy naked slides.

00:11:14.150 --> 00:11:15.750
I'll show you what I
mean by that later.

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:18.124
But you don't want to expose
the whole slide to everybody

00:11:18.124 --> 00:11:20.630
and shock them.

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:22.010
Thou shalt not print large.

00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:25.360
The important people
sit in the front.

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:29.120
So who cares about
the guys in the back?

00:11:29.120 --> 00:11:31.220
Thou shalt not use color.

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:35.430
Use of color indicates
uncareful research.

00:11:35.430 --> 00:11:37.260
You're emphasizing
some words over others,

00:11:37.260 --> 00:11:40.020
and it's just too
showy to use color.

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:41.340
Thou shalt not illustrate.

00:11:41.340 --> 00:11:44.340
Confucius says, a picture's
worth 10,000 words.

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:47.720
Who cares about the
wisdom of the ages, right?

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:50.910
And thou shalt not
make eye contact.

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:53.160
You want to be humble, kind
of pretend to be humble

00:11:53.160 --> 00:11:58.740
and keep your eyes down and
try not to let anybody see you.

00:11:58.740 --> 00:12:00.562
Thou shalt not skip
slides in a long talk.

00:12:00.562 --> 00:12:02.187
I guarantee you, in
this room, somebody

00:12:02.187 --> 00:12:05.555
has looked at their watch,
seen how many slides they have.

00:12:05.555 --> 00:12:08.030
And their solution is,
I'll just talk faster.

00:12:08.030 --> 00:12:09.040
That's what people do.

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:10.040
You prepared the slides.

00:12:10.040 --> 00:12:10.880
They want to see them all.

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:12.921
And if you have to, just
cut off the conclusions,

00:12:12.921 --> 00:12:15.576
the last couple of slides
if you run out of time.

00:12:15.576 --> 00:12:16.950
And then this is
the golden rule.

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:20.120
This one can save you, even
if you violate the others.

00:12:20.120 --> 00:12:21.400
Thou shalt not practice.

00:12:21.400 --> 00:12:25.390
How can you be spontaneous
if you practice?

00:12:25.390 --> 00:12:28.170
It'll feel practiced
if you practice.

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:29.350
So don't do that.

00:12:29.350 --> 00:12:32.790
That's the last
thing you should do.

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:34.360
So here's an
example of doing it.

00:12:34.360 --> 00:12:38.160
It actually says PowerPoint,
but it's using Google Slides.

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:40.450
So trying these commandments.

00:12:40.450 --> 00:12:44.350
So print small.

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:46.670
Now these features,
some engineer at Google

00:12:46.670 --> 00:12:47.610
put these features in.

00:12:47.610 --> 00:12:51.280
So you have to use them to
be a good Google employee.

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:54.040
So you want to hide
your naked slides there.

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:55.880
That's some variety.

00:12:55.880 --> 00:12:58.599
But again, no use of color.

00:12:58.599 --> 00:12:59.140
There you go.

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:02.110
That's another
dramatic entrance.

00:13:02.110 --> 00:13:05.670
And then the next one
is just my favorite.

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:07.644
I'm glad somebody
put the time in

00:13:07.644 --> 00:13:09.310
to put this in because
it's very useful.

00:13:12.550 --> 00:13:13.370
There you go.

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:16.460
OK.

00:13:16.460 --> 00:13:18.070
So that was the
bad career advice.

00:13:18.070 --> 00:13:20.450
Let's talk about the
alternative career.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:23.940
This is taken from my career,
which spanned 40 years.

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:26.390
So it's kind of an academic--
I hope it'll apply to here.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:29.000
It's in systems, not in theory.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.530
And I'll go through
these pieces one by one.

00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:35.770
So advice to writing bad papers.

00:13:35.770 --> 00:13:38.421
And again, I put some
writing tips there.

00:13:38.421 --> 00:13:40.670
The writing tips actually
have some grammatical errors

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:42.180
in them, following
my bad tradition.

00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:44.490
But you can go take a look.

00:13:44.490 --> 00:13:48.230
So do the opposite of the
bad paper commandments.

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:49.360
Do define your terms.

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:51.220
Distinguish will
do from have done.

00:13:51.220 --> 00:13:53.080
If you're writing
for critical review,

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:55.240
reviewers are very
skeptical people.

00:13:55.240 --> 00:13:57.185
They're going to
assume the worst.

00:13:57.185 --> 00:13:59.060
They are much more
impressed if you point out

00:13:59.060 --> 00:14:01.268
the drawbacks rather than
they have to discover them.

00:14:04.360 --> 00:14:07.200
And you have to measure
performance and reference

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:09.550
the work to be a scholar.

00:14:09.550 --> 00:14:13.200
And the good news is you guys
built a wonderful service

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:17.252
to make that much easier to do
these days in Google Scholar.

00:14:17.252 --> 00:14:18.710
The best piece of
advice I ever got

00:14:18.710 --> 00:14:20.640
was to read Strunk and White.

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:22.690
Strunk believed in
brevity so much,

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:25.980
he cheers brevity so much, he
couldn't write a long book.

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:28.640
The book itself is
maybe 80 pages or so,

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.620
and it's chock full
of good advice.

00:14:31.620 --> 00:14:35.850
Then the advice is basically
go kind of top down.

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:39.850
You write a one page outline
with a tentative title

00:14:39.850 --> 00:14:42.690
with budgets, how much
you need to write.

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:47.000
That saves a lot of writing,
if you don't have to do it.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.460
Then a paragraph map, which is
a topic sentence [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:51.550
all the way through.

00:14:51.550 --> 00:14:54.640
And it includes
figures and captions.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.060
Even today in 2016,
it takes forever

00:14:57.060 --> 00:14:59.360
on a computer to draw a figure.

00:14:59.360 --> 00:15:01.822
And since you're probably going
to throw that figure away--

00:15:01.822 --> 00:15:03.405
you'll change it--
the best technology

00:15:03.405 --> 00:15:05.120
to do that today is
go to a whiteboard.

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:06.204
You can have colored pens.

00:15:06.204 --> 00:15:07.953
Take a little cell
phone picture and stick

00:15:07.953 --> 00:15:08.890
that in your document.

00:15:08.890 --> 00:15:11.860
That'll take you 1/10
the time as trying

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:14.680
to do something on a computer
because you might throw it

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:15.930
away.

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:20.480
And then write the draft.

00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:22.440
I like the Scientific
American style,

00:15:22.440 --> 00:15:24.100
which has really long captions.

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:25.220
Not everybody does that.

00:15:25.220 --> 00:15:27.600
But you can move text in there
and associate with the figure.

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:28.600
I think that works well.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:30.272
I really like tables a lot.

00:15:30.272 --> 00:15:31.480
There's a lot of dirty facts.

00:15:31.480 --> 00:15:32.860
I love putting them into tables.

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:35.266
That works well for me.

00:15:35.266 --> 00:15:37.640
Then in terms of when you're
starting to polish the text,

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:38.310
read aloud.

00:15:38.310 --> 00:15:40.450
Your ear is better
than your eyes.

00:15:40.450 --> 00:15:43.610
When I start reading a
document, and I forget,

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:46.284
and I stop saying it
out loud, I lose track.

00:15:46.284 --> 00:15:47.700
But if you hear
the words, you can

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:50.150
hear terrible sentences
and grammatical errors

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:51.710
if you hear it.

00:15:51.710 --> 00:15:52.780
There's technology.

00:15:52.780 --> 00:15:55.381
In fact, I just learned
about this thing.

00:15:55.381 --> 00:15:56.880
It was from an
English professor who

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:59.190
taught a massive open
online course at Berkeley.

00:15:59.190 --> 00:16:00.500
I said, why aren't you
using a grammar checker?

00:16:00.500 --> 00:16:02.291
And she said, this is
the world's best one,

00:16:02.291 --> 00:16:02.990
Pearson Writer.

00:16:02.990 --> 00:16:04.940
And it costs you a
whole $20 a year,

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:08.057
and it'll prevent terrible
grammatical errors.

00:16:08.057 --> 00:16:09.140
And even it'll help style.

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:12.809
In fact, I was thinking,
you guys should buy this.

00:16:12.809 --> 00:16:14.350
It's one of the
things you're missing

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:15.808
from Google Documents
is a really--

00:16:15.808 --> 00:16:17.390
and this is the
world's best one.

00:16:19.930 --> 00:16:22.790
I'm impressed that
they can pull this off.

00:16:22.790 --> 00:16:24.454
And then you get
feedback from friends.

00:16:24.454 --> 00:16:26.120
Of course, to get
feedback from friends,

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:27.994
if you're writing to a
deadline, you actually

00:16:27.994 --> 00:16:30.520
have to get it done
early, which seems

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:34.510
to be science fiction, for
graduate students at least.

00:16:34.510 --> 00:16:35.470
But get it done early.

00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:37.970
Then it gives you time to give
to your friends for feedback.

00:16:37.970 --> 00:16:39.562
You can iterate.

00:16:39.562 --> 00:16:41.020
And if you don't
do that, if you're

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.040
writing something for review,
then who's your reviewer?

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:44.165
It's the program committee.

00:16:44.165 --> 00:16:46.580
And what I've seen sitting
on program committees

00:16:46.580 --> 00:16:49.080
is a lot of the time the paper
gets rejected not because you

00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:49.940
didn't do something.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:51.640
It's because the
program committee

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:53.450
didn't understand what you did.

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:55.230
And if you interact
with outsiders,

00:16:55.230 --> 00:16:57.300
you've got this
chance of clearing

00:16:57.300 --> 00:17:01.350
that up as opposed to if you
just look at it yourself.

00:17:01.350 --> 00:17:02.570
OK.

00:17:02.570 --> 00:17:04.510
How to not write bad papers.

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:05.355
Bad talks.

00:17:05.355 --> 00:17:07.540
Basically, do the opposite
of bad commandments.

00:17:07.540 --> 00:17:11.300
There's two parts,
preparation and practice.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.170
Most people take about
two minutes a slide.

00:17:13.170 --> 00:17:15.240
For some reason, I take
one minute a slide.

00:17:15.240 --> 00:17:16.750
I don't know why.

00:17:16.750 --> 00:17:19.250
You should plan on that, a
minute or a minute and a half,

00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:20.654
so you have plenty of time.

00:17:20.654 --> 00:17:22.570
And leave time for
questions since that's some

00:17:22.570 --> 00:17:25.400
of the most important parts.

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:28.500
Despite Google engineers
putting in spinning text,

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:31.490
don't do that.

00:17:31.490 --> 00:17:33.074
And then, it's not
a speech, if this

00:17:33.074 --> 00:17:34.240
is the first time you do it.

00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:35.020
It's a talk.

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:38.720
So you don't have to memorize
it, but have notes ready.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:42.050
Practice is the key.

00:17:42.050 --> 00:17:45.120
You want to do dry runs with
friends to get feedback.

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:47.780
If you're giving a
professional talk, the way

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:49.930
you make an impression is
not only to give a talk

00:17:49.930 --> 00:17:51.360
but how you answer
the questions.

00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:53.030
I think for those
of us in the field

00:17:53.030 --> 00:17:54.940
a while, when you see
somebody give a dynamic talk,

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.440
and they really
nail the questions,

00:17:56.440 --> 00:17:59.887
you pay attention to that.

00:17:59.887 --> 00:18:02.470
And then so your practice ought
to have really tough questions

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:04.640
so you can practice
tough questions.

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:08.110
And then with modern
cellphones, you

00:18:08.110 --> 00:18:10.990
can record yourself,
not only your audio.

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:12.464
You can watch yourself.

00:18:12.464 --> 00:18:14.880
I got to tell you, it's going
to be a humbling experience.

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:18.980
You'll hear the crutches that
you have in your verbal speech.

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:20.880
I start a lot of
sentences with so.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:21.660
I say huh.

00:18:21.660 --> 00:18:23.500
You'll be shocked how bad it is.

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:26.200
Everybody does it, and this
is the way you get better.

00:18:26.200 --> 00:18:27.450
And I practice everything.

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:29.782
I think of it-- I
practice my talks just

00:18:29.782 --> 00:18:31.490
to show the students
that you're supposed

00:18:31.490 --> 00:18:32.480
to practice your talks.

00:18:32.480 --> 00:18:34.790
But I practice my award
acceptance speeches,

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:37.110
and they tear them apart.

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:39.340
I would think an acceptance
speech is pretty good.

00:18:39.340 --> 00:18:40.412
But no, no.

00:18:40.412 --> 00:18:41.120
Make them better.

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:43.440
So practice.

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:44.040
OK.

00:18:44.040 --> 00:18:47.140
Now the other thing that I
was going to do in this talk

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:50.130
is quote Richard Hamming.

00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:51.970
Richard Hamming actually
came to Berkeley

00:18:51.970 --> 00:18:56.100
when I was young as a
professor, a larval professor.

00:18:56.100 --> 00:18:58.450
And he gave this talk,
"You and Your Research,"

00:18:58.450 --> 00:19:01.410
which is more or less how to
do great research like me.

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:05.220
And so Richard Hamming of
Hamming code, you know,

00:19:05.220 --> 00:19:10.560
Hamming distance, the reason
memories don't make mistakes,

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:13.120
spent his career
mostly at Bell Labs.

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.450
And it's pretty clear
from watching these videos

00:19:15.450 --> 00:19:17.211
he's a very opinionated guy.

00:19:17.211 --> 00:19:19.210
He's not saying, well,
maybe you should do this.

00:19:19.210 --> 00:19:20.310
He says, do this.

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:22.140
But he watched careers
over at Bell Labs.

00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:23.220
He saw people fail.

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:24.720
He saw people succeed.

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:28.899
And I'll quote him, show a
one minute segment every time.

00:19:28.899 --> 00:19:31.440
So this is him talking about
the importance of communication.

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:33.490
And you'll get his
personality from this one.

00:19:33.490 --> 00:19:34.390
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:37.090
-Which brings me to the
topic of communication.

00:19:37.090 --> 00:19:40.045
You need to learn to
communicate orally

00:19:40.045 --> 00:19:43.480
in talks like this,
written in written reports,

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:46.114
and casual conversations.

00:19:46.114 --> 00:19:47.530
In the middle of
a conference, you

00:19:47.530 --> 00:19:48.550
have to be able
to get up and say,

00:19:48.550 --> 00:19:50.100
that's wrong for these reasons.

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:51.450
Bing, bing, bing, bing.

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:53.150
And you win.

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:55.010
If you sit around
and say, well, I'll

00:19:55.010 --> 00:19:57.135
write a report tomorrow
after I've thought about it

00:19:57.135 --> 00:19:58.890
some more, the decision's made.

00:19:58.890 --> 00:20:02.199
We go ahead, and it doesn't
matter what you do then.

00:20:02.199 --> 00:20:03.990
The ability to communicate
at three levels.

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:05.580
Now, how do you learn it?

00:20:05.580 --> 00:20:08.249
You can read books if you
want to, but forget it.

00:20:08.249 --> 00:20:10.040
The way you learn, as
far as I'm concerned,

00:20:10.040 --> 00:20:12.180
is every time you
go to a talk, you

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:15.670
listen, not only to the talk,
but to the style that's done.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:17.320
What talks are effective?

00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:19.010
Why were they affect?

00:20:19.010 --> 00:20:21.844
What aspects of the
speaker can you adapt?

00:20:21.844 --> 00:20:22.687
[END PLAYBACK]

00:20:22.687 --> 00:20:23.520
DAVID PATTERSON: OK.

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:24.170
That's Richard Hamming.

00:20:24.170 --> 00:20:24.460
And then--

00:20:24.460 --> 00:20:25.126
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:20:25.126 --> 00:20:27.110
-Which brings me to the
topic of communication.

00:20:27.110 --> 00:20:31.317
You need to learn to communicate
orally in talks like--

00:20:31.317 --> 00:20:31.900
[END PLAYBACK]

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:32.816
DAVID PATTERSON: Stop.

00:20:32.816 --> 00:20:34.890
Stop, Richard.

00:20:34.890 --> 00:20:38.514
And then he-- he gave
this talk lots of times.

00:20:38.514 --> 00:20:40.430
This is the one that's
on your YouTube, right?

00:20:40.430 --> 00:20:41.510
That's how I found it.

00:20:41.510 --> 00:20:43.217
But there was a text one before.

00:20:43.217 --> 00:20:44.800
And he said, in my
early days, I think

00:20:44.800 --> 00:20:47.560
you should spend as much time on
polishing and presenting as you

00:20:47.560 --> 00:20:49.330
did in the original research.

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:52.060
Now at least 50% of it has
to go in the presentation.

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:56.421
Now if you know Hamming's idea
of how do you encode memory,

00:20:56.421 --> 00:20:58.420
it's beautifully presented
that almost everybody

00:20:58.420 --> 00:20:59.160
can understand.

00:20:59.160 --> 00:21:00.420
So that was an example of him.

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:02.490
He not just came
up with the math,

00:21:02.490 --> 00:21:05.340
but he laid it out and had a
very simple encoding thing.

00:21:05.340 --> 00:21:07.000
It's almost like a parlor trick.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:08.750
You can put a bit
pattern there, and it'll

00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:10.250
tell you which one is wrong
from the way he does it.

00:21:10.250 --> 00:21:12.030
He made it very
easy to understand.

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:15.020
And as a result, every
single computer in the world

00:21:15.020 --> 00:21:16.160
uses his idea.

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:18.899
But that was an example of
him following his own advice.

