00:24:03.417 --> 00:24:06.000
DAVID PATTERSON: And you realize
when he's giving these talks,

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:07.541
the chemists that
he was sitting with

00:24:07.541 --> 00:24:10.020
were still around and could
hear him give these talks.

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:14.180
A charming guy.

00:24:16.930 --> 00:24:17.430
OK.

00:24:17.430 --> 00:24:19.051
So selecting a problem.

00:24:19.051 --> 00:24:21.050
When I started at Berkeley,
I just jumped to it.

00:24:21.050 --> 00:24:22.970
I'll tell you about
it in the next one.

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:24.450
Invent a new field
and stick to it.

00:24:24.450 --> 00:24:24.640
No.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:25.556
Try and do real stuff.

00:24:25.556 --> 00:24:29.725
Make sure other people think
it's important, not just you.

00:24:29.725 --> 00:24:32.090
It's particularly easy
to do that in academia.

00:24:32.090 --> 00:24:35.640
You're aiming for this positive
impact, big impact on computer

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:38.920
science and engineering.

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:41.100
And stick to it
your whole career?

00:24:41.100 --> 00:24:43.330
I think in this fast--
that's not what I did.

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:46.620
In this fast moving
field, why not instead do

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:47.780
a bunch of short projects?

00:24:47.780 --> 00:24:50.113
Because a lot of research
projects aren't going to work.

00:24:52.770 --> 00:24:55.310
These things always take
longer than you expect.

00:24:55.310 --> 00:24:57.560
And how are you going to
know if you work on something

00:24:57.560 --> 00:24:59.976
for 20 years that this is going
to be an important problem

00:24:59.976 --> 00:25:01.960
for 20 years?

00:25:01.960 --> 00:25:05.180
And what we found by doing
lots of five year projects

00:25:05.180 --> 00:25:07.587
is that learning was more
of the number of projects

00:25:07.587 --> 00:25:08.920
than it was the number of years.

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:13.070
As you tackle something, it was
the new thing you learned from.

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:15.742
And then a lot of times--
this, I'll say-- research

00:25:15.742 --> 00:25:16.450
doesn't work out.

00:25:16.450 --> 00:25:21.110
And you'd like to fail sooner
rather than fail later.

00:25:23.910 --> 00:25:26.280
What's worked well for
us is multidisciplinary,

00:25:26.280 --> 00:25:27.760
multi-investigator
projects, trying

00:25:27.760 --> 00:25:32.420
to have somebody from multiple
fields on a single team.

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:34.870
And then try and figure out
the strengths and weaknesses

00:25:34.870 --> 00:25:36.000
of your local environment.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.124
Universities are different.

00:25:37.124 --> 00:25:39.530
There's strengths that
obviously Google has,

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:40.680
and there's weaknesses too.

00:25:40.680 --> 00:25:43.717
So try and figure out something
that matches your environment.

00:25:43.717 --> 00:25:45.800
And make sure it's exciting,
that you want to work

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:46.810
on it for several years.

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:49.766
And what I've found is a
compelling prototype-- if we

00:25:49.766 --> 00:25:51.140
can build this
thing, it's really

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:54.370
going to be amazing--
is inspirational.

00:25:54.370 --> 00:25:56.700
OK, so that's
selecting the problem.

00:25:56.700 --> 00:26:00.070
My first project, when I got
to Berkeley 40 years ago,

00:26:00.070 --> 00:26:02.311
I spent about a week
thinking about it

00:26:02.311 --> 00:26:03.560
and joined some other faculty.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:06.750
And it was
ridiculously ambitious.

00:26:06.750 --> 00:26:09.380
Three hardware faculty were
designing our own instruction

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:12.810
set, build our own chips,
build our own interconnection

00:26:12.810 --> 00:26:15.229
network switches, board
systems, operating systems.

00:26:15.229 --> 00:26:17.020
We didn't have any
experience in any of it.

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:19.170
We didn't have any
research funding.

00:26:19.170 --> 00:26:21.310
We didn't have any
computing or CAD tools.

00:26:21.310 --> 00:26:22.750
So what happened from all that?

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:24.250
You know, a couple
of papers, right?

00:26:24.250 --> 00:26:25.740
Not bad for academics.

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:30.224
Fortunately, I took a sabbatical
during that time and went away.

00:26:30.224 --> 00:26:32.640
And it gave me a chance to
think about things differently.

00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:34.265
And I came back and
did the RISC stuff.

00:26:34.265 --> 00:26:38.700
Otherwise, I wouldn't
have tenure today.

00:26:38.700 --> 00:26:40.140
Picking a solution.

00:26:40.140 --> 00:26:41.810
Let complexity be your guide?

00:26:41.810 --> 00:26:42.880
No.

00:26:42.880 --> 00:26:45.370
Keep things simple, unless
you've got a really good reason

00:26:45.370 --> 00:26:47.190
not to.

00:26:47.190 --> 00:26:49.340
I came up with this
phrase early in my career.

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:50.510
It's intelligence beans.

00:26:50.510 --> 00:26:52.760
On any project, you have a
sack of intelligence beans

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:54.060
that you get to spend.

00:26:54.060 --> 00:26:57.810
So decide where you want to
spend your intelligence beans.

00:26:57.810 --> 00:26:59.612
And then were it
doesn't matter, you

00:26:59.612 --> 00:27:00.820
can use the common solutions.

00:27:00.820 --> 00:27:02.690
And the best result
you can possibly get

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:04.670
is afterwards for
them to say, anyone

00:27:04.670 --> 00:27:06.002
could have thought of that.

00:27:06.002 --> 00:27:08.122
That doesn't seem
so complicated.

00:27:08.122 --> 00:27:09.580
Anybody could have
thought of that.

00:27:09.580 --> 00:27:11.470
You've achieved things well.

00:27:11.470 --> 00:27:14.120
Complexity costs everything.

00:27:14.120 --> 00:27:16.740
Longer design, construction,
testing, and debugging.

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:19.157
And these delays lessen
the impact of what you do.

00:27:19.157 --> 00:27:20.240
So try and keep it simple.

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:23.620
It's hard to keep things
simple, but that's the goal.

00:27:23.620 --> 00:27:24.680
The computer scientific?

00:27:24.680 --> 00:27:25.571
Nope.

00:27:25.571 --> 00:27:27.820
You want to run experiments
to discover real problems.

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:29.450
And as my friend John
[INAUDIBLE] says,

00:27:29.450 --> 00:27:32.970
you use your intuition to ask
questions, not to answer them.

00:27:32.970 --> 00:27:34.190
We're really smart people.

00:27:34.190 --> 00:27:36.470
We can make up what we
think the answer is.

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:38.215
But that doesn't
mean they're right.

00:27:38.215 --> 00:27:40.090
What we need is to figure
out the experiments

00:27:40.090 --> 00:27:42.410
to figure out the real answers.

00:27:42.410 --> 00:27:45.060
So at Berkeley,
they ask me, well,

00:27:45.060 --> 00:27:47.600
how do you pick a
problem and solution?

00:27:47.600 --> 00:27:49.600
What we've done
over these years,

00:27:49.600 --> 00:27:54.670
these five year projects is
before the end of a project,

00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:56.550
we start meeting
for at least a year

00:27:56.550 --> 00:27:58.730
to start talking about
what the next one would be.

00:27:58.730 --> 00:28:00.480
We spend that much
time thinking about it.

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:02.275
Typically, what
we've done is saying,

00:28:02.275 --> 00:28:04.275
what are some interesting
technology trends that

00:28:04.275 --> 00:28:06.120
are happening over
the next five or 10

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:08.160
years that will shape
the future of computing

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:09.730
eight to 10 years out?

00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:11.340
To see if the mix
of these trends

00:28:11.340 --> 00:28:13.560
have some new opportunity.

00:28:13.560 --> 00:28:17.400
For RISC, it was probably
computer scientists

00:28:17.400 --> 00:28:20.330
being able to do
integrated circuit design.

00:28:20.330 --> 00:28:22.270
There was Moore's law
that was taking off.

00:28:22.270 --> 00:28:24.830
So a 32-bit microprocessor
was plausible.

00:28:24.830 --> 00:28:27.260
What's the right way to
design such a microprocessor?

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:31.310
For RAID, personal computers
were getting popular.

00:28:31.310 --> 00:28:33.060
They started building
hard disks for them,

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:35.360
these so-called
small hard disks.

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:37.620
They were inexpensive.

00:28:37.620 --> 00:28:40.590
Performance for input,
output was slow.

00:28:40.590 --> 00:28:42.720
Processors were getting
faster because of RISC.

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:43.820
Disk performance was slow.

00:28:43.820 --> 00:28:46.710
Maybe we could do something
with a lot of them.

00:28:46.710 --> 00:28:48.680
For the Network of
Workstation projects,

00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:50.810
not only were workstations
getting really fast,

00:28:50.810 --> 00:28:53.970
but there were beginning to be
local area networks switches.

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:55.790
Could we just build
a big computer out

00:28:55.790 --> 00:28:57.430
of a bunch of these components?

00:28:57.430 --> 00:28:58.650
And then how would that work?

00:29:02.282 --> 00:29:04.240
Another thing that we've
noticed over the years

00:29:04.240 --> 00:29:05.550
is when you're all by
yourself, and you're

00:29:05.550 --> 00:29:07.750
going to work in a new
field, it's very scary.

00:29:07.750 --> 00:29:10.540
But if there's a group of
you with different areas,

00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:12.644
and you kind of go
after this thing,

00:29:12.644 --> 00:29:14.060
there's kind of
safety in numbers.

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:15.704
You aren't all
risking your careers

00:29:15.704 --> 00:29:16.870
working on machine learning.

00:29:16.870 --> 00:29:18.411
But the three of
you working together

00:29:18.411 --> 00:29:22.290
seems not quite as scary
to be able to do that.

00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:27.400
And a big thing when
you've got these ideas

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:30.430
is to find people whose
opinion you trust and try

00:29:30.430 --> 00:29:33.129
and get their feedback to
help you shape your vision.

00:29:33.129 --> 00:29:34.920
You don't have to do
exactly what they say,

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:36.700
but you ought to hear
what they're saying.

00:29:36.700 --> 00:29:39.540
And then pick a good name.

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:41.140
Apparently in some
parallel universe,

00:29:41.140 --> 00:29:42.910
I'm in the marketing department.

00:29:42.910 --> 00:29:45.260
But it's not that hard.

00:29:45.260 --> 00:29:46.760
I have these
friends who show off

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:51.140
their Latin education who pick
some name nobody can possibly

00:29:51.140 --> 00:29:51.640
spell.

00:29:51.640 --> 00:29:53.181
And they even have
a word for it now.

00:29:53.181 --> 00:29:56.060
You pick the name, and then
you backfill in the acronym.

00:29:56.060 --> 00:29:58.130
And so they're called
backronyms, right?

00:29:58.130 --> 00:30:00.130
Nobody's ever going
to remember that.

00:30:00.130 --> 00:30:02.880
One of the projects my younger
colleagues picked is aspire.

00:30:02.880 --> 00:30:05.030
It's actually 11 or 12 words.

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:06.760
Nobody but him can remember.

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:09.739
So if that's true-- if you're
going to use the acronym model,

00:30:09.739 --> 00:30:11.780
it's got to be three or
four letters if anybody's

00:30:11.780 --> 00:30:14.200
going to remember it.

00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:16.120
The way we do it is
put a bunch of words

00:30:16.120 --> 00:30:18.120
on the wall that
describe the project.

00:30:18.120 --> 00:30:19.630
Vowels are really valuable.

00:30:19.630 --> 00:30:22.727
And you want to try, three or
four letters-- three or four

00:30:22.727 --> 00:30:25.870
letters that are an English
word that kind of have something

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:27.444
to do with the project.

00:30:27.444 --> 00:30:28.860
But I'm available
as a consultant.

00:30:32.230 --> 00:30:33.430
Running a project.

00:30:33.430 --> 00:30:35.709
You want to avoid feedback?

00:30:35.709 --> 00:30:36.750
That's one of the themes.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:37.250
No.

00:30:37.250 --> 00:30:39.590
We do these periodic project
reviews with outsiders.

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:42.850
We've been doing them for 30
years, twice a year, three day

00:30:42.850 --> 00:30:43.350
retreats.

00:30:43.350 --> 00:30:47.290
How many people here have been
to a Berkeley style retreat?

00:30:47.290 --> 00:30:47.790
All right.

00:30:47.790 --> 00:30:48.982
That's like a dozen of you.

00:30:52.360 --> 00:30:57.970
And the outsiders are valued.

00:30:57.970 --> 00:31:00.930
Huge benefits to doing this.

00:31:00.930 --> 00:31:03.087
At the end, we get the
feedback from everybody.

00:31:03.087 --> 00:31:04.670
And we don't argue
with that feedback.

00:31:04.670 --> 00:31:06.430
We try and understand it.

00:31:06.430 --> 00:31:09.902
It also creates deadlines,
which are tough everywhere,

00:31:09.902 --> 00:31:11.110
but particularly in academia.

00:31:11.110 --> 00:31:13.400
It builds team spirit.

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:15.030
And for the people
working on it,

00:31:15.030 --> 00:31:17.030
it gives them a chance
to communicate and spread

00:31:17.030 --> 00:31:20.106
their ideas,
interact with others.

00:31:20.106 --> 00:31:21.480
Consider a mid-course
correction.

00:31:21.480 --> 00:31:23.320
Our first project
that I was doing-- it

00:31:23.320 --> 00:31:24.864
was a multi-processor.

00:31:24.864 --> 00:31:26.780
The RISC ideas were just
starting to catch on,

00:31:26.780 --> 00:31:28.280
but they hadn't
been commercial yet.

00:31:28.280 --> 00:31:29.830
But by midway
through the project,

00:31:29.830 --> 00:31:33.040
there were commercial
chips like MIPS and SPARC.

00:31:33.040 --> 00:31:35.761
We should have
redirected our project

00:31:35.761 --> 00:31:37.260
to be used in
commercial processors.

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:40.230
But I felt like that was
breaking our promise,

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:42.807
and we should have stuck with
the ones that we did custom.

00:31:42.807 --> 00:31:44.390
But we'd have had a
much bigger impact

00:31:44.390 --> 00:31:46.934
with a multi-processor
RISC project

00:31:46.934 --> 00:31:48.850
then if we'd used
commercial instruction sets.

00:31:48.850 --> 00:31:50.710
So that's part of
our culture now.

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:51.984
It's a five year project.

00:31:51.984 --> 00:31:53.650
Two and a half years
in, maybe the world

00:31:53.650 --> 00:31:54.671
has changed in some way.

00:31:54.671 --> 00:31:56.170
And you should take
advantage of it.

00:31:56.170 --> 00:31:58.812
An example of that would
have been the RAD Lab, which

00:31:58.812 --> 00:32:00.020
was a couple of projects ago.

00:32:00.020 --> 00:32:01.810
We were doing internet services.

00:32:01.810 --> 00:32:04.350
And then cloud computing
got popular in it.

00:32:04.350 --> 00:32:09.310
So we embraced that, and that
became a big theme of RAD Lab.

00:32:09.310 --> 00:32:12.750
Pick the size and the members
of the team carefully.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:15.170
Tough personalities are
hard on everybody, not just

00:32:15.170 --> 00:32:17.680
tough personalities for faculty,
even tough personalities

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:19.010
for students.

00:32:19.010 --> 00:32:21.160
It can make it no
fun to come to work.

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:23.080
So try and get good people.

00:32:23.080 --> 00:32:24.820
I think Berkeley
consciously tries

00:32:24.820 --> 00:32:27.710
not to hire Prima Donnas,
which makes it nicer.

00:32:27.710 --> 00:32:30.980
And if you have one expert per
area, it's a little easier.

00:32:30.980 --> 00:32:32.817
My colleague,
Kathy Yelick-- I've

00:32:32.817 --> 00:32:34.900
got opinions about programming
language compilers,

00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:37.710
but when she speaks, I listen.

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:39.980
And that makes it
easier to do things.

00:32:39.980 --> 00:32:41.590
Don't be distracted by others?

00:32:41.590 --> 00:32:44.210
This is not going to be
so radical for you guys.

00:32:44.210 --> 00:32:49.340
But about 10 years ago, we went
to an open collaborative thing,

00:32:49.340 --> 00:32:51.650
where we got rid
of faculty offices.

00:32:51.650 --> 00:32:54.610
What was happening is that
the students were staying home

00:32:54.610 --> 00:32:57.460
because the computers were just
as fast, the networks just as

00:32:57.460 --> 00:32:58.964
fast at home as
they were at work.

00:32:58.964 --> 00:33:00.880
And whether this is good
for a company or not,

00:33:00.880 --> 00:33:01.670
I'll leave to you.

00:33:01.670 --> 00:33:03.836
But it's terrible for
research because it's not just

00:33:03.836 --> 00:33:05.478
put your head down
and plow ahead.

00:33:05.478 --> 00:33:07.852
You've got to talk to people
because you're not sure what

00:33:07.852 --> 00:33:09.920
you're supposed to be doing.

00:33:09.920 --> 00:33:12.600
So we put it into
the open space.

00:33:12.600 --> 00:33:16.050
And now that I've read about
it, what you're shooting for

00:33:16.050 --> 00:33:18.160
is communication
and concentration.

00:33:18.160 --> 00:33:20.042
So people can come in to work.

00:33:20.042 --> 00:33:21.500
They have to be
able to concentrate

00:33:21.500 --> 00:33:22.590
enough to get the work done.

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:24.820
But you want to have
spontaneous communication, which

00:33:24.820 --> 00:33:26.260
leads to innovation.

00:33:26.260 --> 00:33:29.840
So bump into each other
and have meeting rooms.

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:32.300
We've got the meeting rooms
optimized for discussions

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:33.350
and phone calls.

00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:36.157
Jeff Walz brought us
probably 10 years ago.

00:33:36.157 --> 00:33:38.490
And we saw what you guys did
with your conference rooms,

00:33:38.490 --> 00:33:42.220
and we imitated that.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:44.940
And like you guys, we have
kitchens and free drinks.

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:49.020
We can't do food,
but we can do drinks.

00:33:49.020 --> 00:33:51.460
And the amazing thing,
it accelerates research.

00:33:51.460 --> 00:33:54.580
Who would've thought space
could accelerate research?

00:33:54.580 --> 00:33:57.550
It was startling what happened.

00:33:57.550 --> 00:34:01.390
We went from faculty offices
that had kind of white boards

00:34:01.390 --> 00:34:03.394
there that were filled
with faculty reminders.

00:34:03.394 --> 00:34:04.060
And you came in.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:05.820
You got to work on,
like, one square foot

00:34:05.820 --> 00:34:07.180
to put your idea in there.

00:34:07.180 --> 00:34:10.120
Instead, we had
giant whiteboards.

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:11.670
There was no writing.

00:34:11.670 --> 00:34:13.790
You couldn't reserve it
in the high tech way.

00:34:13.790 --> 00:34:16.110
You copied it with cell phones.

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:17.170
It became stimulating.

00:34:17.170 --> 00:34:18.270
People came in more.

00:34:18.270 --> 00:34:21.420
There were more
spontaneous meetings.

00:34:21.420 --> 00:34:25.000
And then we noticed the zero
to 60 time for new people

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.409
went incredibly faster by
having that kind of environment.

00:34:28.409 --> 00:34:33.210
So Matei Zaharia-- in
his second semester

00:34:33.210 --> 00:34:35.070
there, he gave a talk
at Carnegie Mellon.

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:37.510
And we've never had
anybody do that before.

00:34:37.510 --> 00:34:39.759
Now Matei Zaharia, who's
the founder of Spark,

00:34:39.759 --> 00:34:40.800
did a lot of good things.

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:42.727
But it wasn't
obvious then that he

00:34:42.727 --> 00:34:44.560
was going to be that
good, as it turned out.

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:48.179
And so maybe that had
something to do with it.

00:34:48.179 --> 00:34:50.560
And so Richard
Hamming has opinions

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:53.440
on this, based on
his experience,

00:34:53.440 --> 00:34:54.940
which I'm sure
you're not surprised.

00:34:54.940 --> 00:34:55.440
OK.

00:34:55.440 --> 00:34:56.550
He's got two opinions.

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:58.870
The first one is open
versus closed doors.

00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:00.820
And the only way he
can have this opinion

00:35:00.820 --> 00:35:02.690
was to keep track of
all of his colleagues,

00:35:02.690 --> 00:35:04.620
which ones kept the doors
closed, which ones were open,

00:35:04.620 --> 00:35:06.190
and which ones were successful.

00:35:06.190 --> 00:35:10.124
And here's his idea.

00:35:10.124 --> 00:35:10.822
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:35:10.822 --> 00:35:12.280
-The example I've
given you already

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:14.600
is working with the
door closed or open.

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:16.489
If you work with
your door closed,

00:35:16.489 --> 00:35:17.530
you won't be interrupted.

00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:19.015
You'll get your work done.

00:35:19.015 --> 00:35:20.640
If you work with your
door open, people

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:23.960
come by and stop and
chat and so on and so on.

00:35:23.960 --> 00:35:27.140
But I've noticed very
clearly at Bell Laboratories

00:35:27.140 --> 00:35:30.790
those work with the door
shut may be working just as

00:35:30.790 --> 00:35:34.600
hard 10 years later, but they
don't know what to work on.

00:35:34.600 --> 00:35:36.960
They are not connected
with reality.

00:35:36.960 --> 00:35:39.610
Those who had the door
open may very well

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:41.920
know what's important.

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:45.740
Now I cannot prove to you
whether the open door causes

00:35:45.740 --> 00:35:49.030
the open mind or whether the
open mind causes the open door.

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:50.840
I suspect both.

00:35:50.840 --> 00:35:52.860
I can only establish
the correlation.

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:55.390
And it was quite spectacular.

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:58.680
Almost always, the
guys with the door

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:01.190
closed were often very
well able, very gifted.

00:36:01.190 --> 00:36:05.530
But they seemed to work always
on slightly the wrong problem.

00:36:05.530 --> 00:36:09.020
So you have to get a wide
feeling for what is going on.

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:09.980
[END PLAYBACK]

00:36:09.980 --> 00:36:11.160
DAVID PATTERSON: OK.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:14.050
And then he believed
that so much,

00:36:14.050 --> 00:36:16.880
that this is how his patterns--
how he handled Friday

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:18.590
afternoons, about
the importance,

00:36:18.590 --> 00:36:21.470
especially for researchers--
you can start work really hard.

00:36:21.470 --> 00:36:24.460
But you could miss the
really important thing

00:36:24.460 --> 00:36:26.662
by not interacting.

00:36:26.662 --> 00:36:27.650
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:36:27.650 --> 00:36:29.880
-At the urging of some other
people partly and partly

00:36:29.880 --> 00:36:33.930
of my own, I used to set
aside Friday noon and Friday

00:36:33.930 --> 00:36:38.776
afternoon for great
thoughts, meaning, yes, I'll

00:36:38.776 --> 00:36:39.650
answer the telephone.

00:36:39.650 --> 00:36:41.330
Yes, I'll sign a sheet of paper.

00:36:41.330 --> 00:36:46.420
But mainly, what is the effect
of computing on science?

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:49.450
What the hell am I doing
with this computing machine?

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:52.170
How is it going to affect AT&amp;T?

00:36:52.170 --> 00:36:54.320
What should I be
doing in computing?

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:57.000
What is the nature of software?

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.430
My friends all after
a while got to know.

00:36:59.430 --> 00:37:01.980
Friday afternoon
is great thoughts.

00:37:01.980 --> 00:37:04.280
What's the nature of this,
that, and the other thing?

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:08.170
I spent 10% of my time trying
to answer the question,

00:37:08.170 --> 00:37:11.490
what are the important
problems in my field?

00:37:11.490 --> 00:37:14.390
10%, Friday afternoon,
straight through.

00:37:14.390 --> 00:37:16.140
Don't do it Monday
morning, because you'll

00:37:16.140 --> 00:37:17.280
be interrupted immediately.

00:37:17.280 --> 00:37:18.565
If you do it Friday
afternoon, some of it's

00:37:18.565 --> 00:37:20.160
going to linger over
onto Saturday and Sunday.

00:37:20.160 --> 00:37:21.470
If you do it Monday
morning, there's

00:37:21.470 --> 00:37:23.830
a hot conference at 10
o'clock, and bingo, everything

00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:25.530
is broken up.

00:37:25.530 --> 00:37:27.460
I used Friday afternoon
for many, many years.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:32.830
I recommend that you find a
regular time to stop and think,

00:37:32.830 --> 00:37:34.440
what are the important things?

00:37:34.440 --> 00:37:35.730
What is going on?

00:37:35.730 --> 00:37:38.530
What is the nature of
what you are doing?

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:41.010
What is the
characteristic of the job?

00:37:41.010 --> 00:37:42.510
What are the
fundamentals behind it?

00:37:42.510 --> 00:37:45.150
So you'll have some idea
of where you're headed,

00:37:45.150 --> 00:37:47.140
so you can march in
a uniform direction

00:37:47.140 --> 00:37:49.410
and get far rather than
being a drunken sailor

00:37:49.410 --> 00:37:51.160
and getting nowhere.

00:37:51.160 --> 00:37:52.460
[END PLAYBACK]

00:37:52.460 --> 00:37:54.710
DAVID PATTERSON: And you're
free to ignore his advice,

00:37:54.710 --> 00:37:58.160
but then your career is
that of a drunken sailor.

00:37:58.160 --> 00:37:58.660
OK.

00:37:58.660 --> 00:37:59.493
Finishing a project.

00:37:59.493 --> 00:38:02.190
I'll talk about this.

00:38:02.190 --> 00:38:04.610
People count the number
of projects you finish,

00:38:04.610 --> 00:38:06.990
not the ones you start.

00:38:06.990 --> 00:38:09.140
And successful
projects go through

00:38:09.140 --> 00:38:12.990
this unglamorous hard phase
of trying to finish it.

00:38:12.990 --> 00:38:14.740
And it's because design
is a lot more fun.

00:38:14.740 --> 00:38:18.300
It's a lot more fun to design
things, to make stuff work.

00:38:18.300 --> 00:38:20.490
But some positive things.

00:38:20.490 --> 00:38:22.240
Fred Brooks, one
of my heroes, says,

00:38:22.240 --> 00:38:24.900
there's no winners on a losing
team, no losers on a winning

00:38:24.900 --> 00:38:25.630
team.

00:38:25.630 --> 00:38:29.820
If you win, anybody involved, no
matter what they did, they win.

00:38:29.820 --> 00:38:31.660
Improve productivity
of team members.

00:38:31.660 --> 00:38:33.530
How can you do that?

00:38:33.530 --> 00:38:34.990
Organize each day.

00:38:34.990 --> 00:38:38.330
Figure out when you're most
alert, when you need a nap

00:38:38.330 --> 00:38:41.130
or exercise or sleep.

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:44.720
When, how often should you
be reading and writing,

00:38:44.720 --> 00:38:48.080
programming and email?

00:38:48.080 --> 00:38:50.610
And what I found, for
successful colleagues,

00:38:50.610 --> 00:38:53.910
they always used to do lists,
daily, weekly, and even

00:38:53.910 --> 00:38:57.880
every six months to see how
they're doing on their career.

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:00.310
These days, there's this
idea of agile scrum,

00:39:00.310 --> 00:39:02.770
where you meet in the same
place at the same time

00:39:02.770 --> 00:39:03.500
and do sprints.

00:39:03.500 --> 00:39:06.150
I think this is a
pretty effective model.

00:39:06.150 --> 00:39:08.020
And then reduce the
project if it's late.

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:11.210
Again, Fred Brooks said,
adding people to a late project

00:39:11.210 --> 00:39:15.260
makes it later in his classic
book, "The Mythical Man-Month."

00:39:15.260 --> 00:39:17.980
And finishing a project
is how you acquire taste.

00:39:17.980 --> 00:39:19.176
How do you get good taste?

00:39:19.176 --> 00:39:21.050
If you don't finish it,
you don't know really

00:39:21.050 --> 00:39:21.872
what went wrong.

00:39:21.872 --> 00:39:23.330
And it helps you
pick good problems

00:39:23.330 --> 00:39:26.030
and find simple solutions.

00:39:26.030 --> 00:39:26.710
OK.

00:39:26.710 --> 00:39:30.390
And then my friend
John Hennessy,

00:39:30.390 --> 00:39:32.450
President of Stanford,
said this a long time ago.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:34.130
You can quickly
tell whether or not

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:36.950
the authors have ever built
something and made it work.

00:39:36.950 --> 00:39:39.890
And if you never make it work,
you don't acquire that taste.

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:43.361
Evaluating quantitatively,
never be proven wrong?

00:39:43.361 --> 00:39:43.860
Nope.

00:39:43.860 --> 00:39:47.390
If you can't be proven wrong,
then you can't be proven right.

00:39:47.390 --> 00:39:49.824
And you have to-- we need
reproducible results.

00:39:49.824 --> 00:39:51.740
You're trying to get
people to use your ideas.

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:52.880
If they can't reproduce
them, they're not

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:54.171
going to take your word for it.

00:39:57.190 --> 00:39:59.780
And for better or for worse,
benchmarks shape our field

00:39:59.780 --> 00:40:01.700
and especially in
the commercial world.

00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:04.350
If we have good ones,
it accelerates progress.

00:40:04.350 --> 00:40:07.240
Bad ones, then there's a
choice between helping sales

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:09.370
or helping customers.

00:40:09.370 --> 00:40:10.455
And often, sales wins.

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:15.924
And then transferring
technology.

00:40:15.924 --> 00:40:17.340
It's not just you
write the paper,

00:40:17.340 --> 00:40:19.400
and everybody starts using it.

00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:22.060
You have to go out and stump it.

00:40:22.060 --> 00:40:24.360
This last year,
there's RISC-V, which

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:27.560
is an effort to be able to
have an open instruction

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:30.680
set, an open alternative,
kind of like Linux

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:32.610
is to Microsoft Windows.

00:40:32.610 --> 00:40:36.157
So I gave talks
at 10 universities

00:40:36.157 --> 00:40:37.740
this fall to try and
get the word out.

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.230
Then if they kind
of like the ideas,

00:40:39.230 --> 00:40:40.313
then they read the papers.

00:40:43.240 --> 00:40:45.240
Of course, if you don't
pick a good problem,

00:40:45.240 --> 00:40:46.990
people aren't going
to be that interested.

00:40:46.990 --> 00:40:49.430
And you can tell if it's a
good problem if more people get

00:40:49.430 --> 00:40:52.310
interested over time rather
than yours start to do that.

00:40:52.310 --> 00:40:53.710
I think I am persuasive.

00:40:53.710 --> 00:40:56.710
The way I change minds is
with believable numbers.

00:40:56.710 --> 00:40:59.854
And so you have to collect that
quantitatively and believe it.

00:40:59.854 --> 00:41:01.645
The other thing I
learned late in my career

00:41:01.645 --> 00:41:04.390
is your personality affects
technology transfer.

00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:06.560
There's this person who
I won't name who had

00:41:06.560 --> 00:41:07.930
a bunch of interesting ideas.

00:41:07.930 --> 00:41:09.201
And people wouldn't use them.

00:41:09.201 --> 00:41:10.950
And I talked to people
in the industry it.

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:12.552
They hated that guy.

00:41:12.552 --> 00:41:13.470
They hated that guy.

00:41:13.470 --> 00:41:16.880
If there was any other
way to do it at all,

00:41:16.880 --> 00:41:19.252
they would use it
because that was

00:41:19.252 --> 00:41:20.460
the last thing they would do.

00:41:20.460 --> 00:41:23.664
So you can be a jerk if you
have the only possible solution.

00:41:23.664 --> 00:41:25.580
But it's kind of hard
to do that in computing.

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:28.290
Maybe in biology,
you can do that.

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:30.520
And then product groups.

00:41:30.520 --> 00:41:31.880
People don't want to change.

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:33.430
There's risk
associated with change.

00:41:33.430 --> 00:41:35.050
It's worked for us.

00:41:35.050 --> 00:41:37.810
And this goes back--
so Fred Brooks,

00:41:37.810 --> 00:41:41.355
when he was a graduate student,
his advisor was Howard Aiken.

00:41:41.355 --> 00:41:43.282
And Fred Brooks says,
I think these people

00:41:43.282 --> 00:41:44.490
are going to steal your idea.

00:41:44.490 --> 00:41:46.510
These companies are
looking at his idea

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:49.490
at Harvard University,
a drum memory system.

00:41:49.490 --> 00:41:51.140
Watch out, Howard.

00:41:51.140 --> 00:41:52.975
And what Aiken said
in a southern accent

00:41:52.975 --> 00:41:54.440
is, "The problem
in this business

00:41:54.440 --> 00:41:56.356
isn't to keep people
from stealing your ideas.

00:41:56.356 --> 00:41:58.085
It's making them
steal your ideas."

00:41:58.085 --> 00:42:02.140
And that's still true
today, 65 years later.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:06.580
So what's worked for us is to
find one bold group, often not

00:42:06.580 --> 00:42:10.240
the leaders, but some bold group
willing to take a shot on it.

00:42:10.240 --> 00:42:11.680
And they are successful.

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:14.970
And then kind of the rest
of the field is-- for us,

00:42:14.970 --> 00:42:18.720
it was Sun Microsystems for RISC
and EMC for RAID and Inktomi

00:42:18.720 --> 00:42:20.985
and then Google for
Networks of Workstations.

00:42:20.985 --> 00:42:22.860
But it's kind of like
the rest of the field--

00:42:22.860 --> 00:42:25.410
oh, damn, they tried it.

00:42:25.410 --> 00:42:26.000
It works.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.090
OK, we'll change.

00:42:27.090 --> 00:42:28.160
Right?

00:42:28.160 --> 00:42:30.635
People don't really-- as
much as people enjoy ideas,

00:42:30.635 --> 00:42:32.010
they don't want
to take the risk.

00:42:32.010 --> 00:42:34.051
And then the other way of
transferring technology

00:42:34.051 --> 00:42:35.420
is to start a company.

00:42:35.420 --> 00:42:37.840
In my 40 years,
everybody I've talked

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:42.760
to who's worked for a
startup likes doing it once.

00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:43.260
Absolutely.

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:45.676
Now, there's some people who
love doing it more than once.

00:42:45.676 --> 00:42:47.790
A lot of people, once is enough.

00:42:47.790 --> 00:42:49.360
But everybody thinks
it was useful.

00:42:49.360 --> 00:42:51.530
They learn a lot.

00:42:51.530 --> 00:42:53.580
And then if it works,
if it works out,

00:42:53.580 --> 00:42:56.080
you see not just your
ideas but the product.

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:58.380
And of course, you can
potentially make a lot of money

00:42:58.380 --> 00:43:01.540
if that works out
and become famous.

00:43:01.540 --> 00:43:04.720
The downsides are that
you learn about things

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:09.310
you might not want to learn
about, particularly lawsuits.

00:43:09.310 --> 00:43:11.410
My friends have had
a lot of lawsuits.

00:43:11.410 --> 00:43:12.830
That's less fun.

00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:15.540
And you don't get to do
research and development.

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:17.870
And then only 10% of the
startups make it, right?

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:21.370
But nevertheless, everybody
thinks it was worth it for once

00:43:21.370 --> 00:43:23.260
in their life, maybe
when you're younger.

00:43:23.260 --> 00:43:25.040
So I didn't really
realize that there

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:27.250
were six roles to being
a leader of a project,

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:29.440
and it changes over time.

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:32.770
But that's what I believe now.

00:43:32.770 --> 00:43:36.350
So wrapping things up-- and
there's time for questions

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:37.110
here.

00:43:37.110 --> 00:43:38.430
The goal is to have impact.

00:43:38.430 --> 00:43:41.300
Does it change the way people
do computing and engineering

00:43:41.300 --> 00:43:42.120
in a positive way?

00:43:42.120 --> 00:43:45.020
Now, we do these
five year projects.

00:43:45.020 --> 00:43:50.680
Now that my career is
ending, I will do 12, right?

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:51.420
They overlap.

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:54.112
So I've been there 40
years, not 60 years.

00:43:54.112 --> 00:43:56.320
You can't tell if a project's
successful for at least

00:43:56.320 --> 00:43:56.970
10 years.

00:43:56.970 --> 00:43:59.600
And the good news
is three of them

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:01.430
look like they're
pretty successful.

00:44:01.430 --> 00:44:02.330
They're 10 years old.

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:05.860
So that's kind of 25%
batting average, which I'm

00:44:05.860 --> 00:44:07.390
glad I did a lot of projects.

00:44:07.390 --> 00:44:11.880
There are two that are finished,
but it hasn't been 10 years.

00:44:11.880 --> 00:44:14.270
The RAD Lab did Spark and Mesos.

00:44:14.270 --> 00:44:15.640
Those seem promising.

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:19.210
The Par Lab did communication
avoiding algorithm [INAUDIBLE]

00:44:19.210 --> 00:44:20.710
and this RISC-V stuff.

00:44:20.710 --> 00:44:22.439
But it'll take
five or seven years

00:44:22.439 --> 00:44:23.730
to know how significant it was.

00:44:23.730 --> 00:44:27.920
So maybe I'll get up to 5
out of 12, which is like 40%.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:29.690
But most of the
projects don't work,

00:44:29.690 --> 00:44:32.710
so I'm glad I did
short projects.

00:44:32.710 --> 00:44:36.060
So solve a problem other people
care about, a taste that you

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:37.910
acquire by finishing projects.

00:44:37.910 --> 00:44:40.450
And then-- whoops.

00:44:40.450 --> 00:44:41.620
So OK.

00:44:41.620 --> 00:44:44.320
And I think the key theme
running over my career

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:46.530
is feedback, is figuring
out ways to get feedback.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:47.030
OK.

00:44:47.030 --> 00:44:49.594
With that, I'm
ready for questions.

