00:45:39.250 --> 00:45:42.590
It looks to me, if I try
to be a neutral observer,

00:45:42.590 --> 00:45:46.810
probably RAID is the
most significant so far.

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:49.350
Which one did I enjoy the most?

00:45:49.350 --> 00:45:51.720
I try and always make
projects that I really love.

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:54.770
I try to make projects that
if I was a graduate student,

00:45:54.770 --> 00:45:58.540
I'd just die to work
on this project.

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:02.670
You know, gee, that's hard.

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:03.170
Maybe--

00:46:03.170 --> 00:46:04.230
AUDIENCE: Which of your
children do you love the most?

00:46:04.230 --> 00:46:07.599
DAVID PATTERSON: Yeah, which of
my children do I love the most?

00:46:07.599 --> 00:46:08.140
I don't know.

00:46:08.140 --> 00:46:10.590
The good thing about all the
projects, whether or not they

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:12.590
were home runs, is they
produced great students.

00:46:12.590 --> 00:46:14.850
And I didn't say
that in the slide.

00:46:14.850 --> 00:46:17.160
There were almost 300
students in those 12 projects.

00:46:20.630 --> 00:46:22.460
I had fun adding that number up.

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:28.039
Jeff.

00:46:28.039 --> 00:46:30.580
AUDIENCE: So this isn't really
a problem for most of us here.

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:32.400
But would you give
different advice

00:46:32.400 --> 00:46:35.440
to a pre-tenure academic
versus a post-tenure academic?

00:46:35.440 --> 00:46:38.606
Or do you think you can
do the kinds of things

00:46:38.606 --> 00:46:40.230
you're talking about
and not compromise

00:46:40.230 --> 00:46:41.310
your chances of getting tenure?

00:46:41.310 --> 00:46:43.184
DAVID PATTERSON: Yeah,
so people ask me this.

00:46:43.184 --> 00:46:47.060
So when Hennessy and I did the
RISC stuff, which at the time

00:46:47.060 --> 00:46:48.920
was hugely controversial--
if you think

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:53.990
deep neural networks
are controversial--

00:46:53.990 --> 00:46:56.350
a faculty member at
another institution

00:46:56.350 --> 00:46:58.890
wrote a hit piece
on me personally.

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:01.390
Dave Patterson's a bad person.

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:05.350
We were talking about
instruction set design.

00:47:05.350 --> 00:47:08.464
But at the time, Hennessy
and I are were saying,

00:47:08.464 --> 00:47:10.380
Digital Equipment, one
of the leading computer

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:13.220
manufacturers in the world,
had a pretty stupid design.

00:47:13.220 --> 00:47:17.940
So yeah, we didn't
worry about that.

00:47:17.940 --> 00:47:21.480
Also, you have to believe
in what you're doing.

00:47:21.480 --> 00:47:23.420
I just can't give the
advice to do something

00:47:23.420 --> 00:47:28.134
that you don't believe in
and work on that, because--

00:47:28.134 --> 00:47:29.800
in fact, when I've
visited universities,

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:32.427
and I've seen that-- this
assistant professor is telling

00:47:32.427 --> 00:47:34.510
me, well, I don't really
like what I'm working on,

00:47:34.510 --> 00:47:36.010
but this is what I have
to do to get tenure.

00:47:36.010 --> 00:47:37.540
And then I go talk
to the chairman.

00:47:37.540 --> 00:47:39.240
This guy's just doing
incremental stuff.

00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:40.531
He's never going to get tenure.

00:47:40.531 --> 00:47:43.370
There's that gap there.

00:47:43.370 --> 00:47:46.265
When you're larval, you need
to make sure you publish.

00:47:46.265 --> 00:47:48.640
You need to go around and give
talks and stuff like that.

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:53.730
But I think you got to do
projects you believe in.

00:47:53.730 --> 00:47:55.930
Otherwise, life's too short
to work on other things.

00:47:55.930 --> 00:47:56.430
Yeah.

00:47:56.430 --> 00:47:57.013
Question here?

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:03.420
AUDIENCE: So you
mentioned a couple times

00:48:03.420 --> 00:48:06.480
not to be a Prima Donna.

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:09.360
So it's easy to identify other
people being Prima Donnas.

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:12.585
But how do you tell if
you're being a Prima Donna?

00:48:12.585 --> 00:48:13.960
DAVID PATTERSON:
Are you married?

00:48:17.240 --> 00:48:20.185
My family's really good
at pointing out my flaws.

00:48:23.110 --> 00:48:27.207
Well, I think feedback
is the one-- I go out

00:48:27.207 --> 00:48:28.290
of my way to get feedback.

00:48:28.290 --> 00:48:31.390
If somebody hates my papers,
I send them new papers

00:48:31.390 --> 00:48:33.930
because they tell me
the honest thing to do.

00:48:33.930 --> 00:48:36.605
I would like to think if
I'm acting like a jerk

00:48:36.605 --> 00:48:39.920
that I'm pretty sure
my friends or my family

00:48:39.920 --> 00:48:40.910
would tell me that.

00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:42.770
I think you could ask.

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:44.260
I think you can ask, right?

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:45.120
Geez.

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:47.190
People are afraid to
tell you something.

00:48:47.190 --> 00:48:52.640
But I think if you asked, did
I handle that well or not-- I

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:56.860
think some people in academia
think that's the way people

00:48:56.860 --> 00:48:57.860
know that you're famous.

00:48:57.860 --> 00:48:58.859
You've had some success.

00:48:58.859 --> 00:49:00.230
You start acting differently.

00:49:00.230 --> 00:49:02.910
It's just bad career advice.

