or six more minutes
for questions.

00:51:05.400 --> 00:51:06.525
DAVID PATTERSON: All right.

00:51:06.525 --> 00:51:11.290
With that, then I need to
quickly give my life story.

00:51:11.290 --> 00:51:12.000
OK.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.960
So I'm an accidental CS student.

00:51:14.960 --> 00:51:18.632
I was a math major and wrestler
in high school and college.

00:51:18.632 --> 00:51:21.090
At the end of my junior year,
the math class was cancelled.

00:51:21.090 --> 00:51:22.500
I had to take a course.

00:51:22.500 --> 00:51:23.590
There was no CS major.

00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:27.230
So I just took intro to computer
science, and I was hooked.

00:51:27.230 --> 00:51:27.910
That was it.

00:51:27.910 --> 00:51:32.700
My senior year, I took every
computer course I could.

00:51:32.700 --> 00:51:34.160
I'm an accidental student.

00:51:34.160 --> 00:51:35.940
I went to UCLA,
graduate student.

00:51:35.940 --> 00:51:37.690
I just casually
mentioned at the end

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.197
of one of those
courses to a new PhD

00:51:40.197 --> 00:51:42.030
that, boy, I'd sure
rather do this than work

00:51:42.030 --> 00:51:43.430
in a factory to pay my college.

00:51:43.430 --> 00:51:44.960
And he on his own
went and found me

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:48.260
a job as undergraduate student.

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:49.947
While I was an
undergraduate student,

00:51:49.947 --> 00:51:52.030
even though it was near
the end of my senior year,

00:51:52.030 --> 00:51:53.946
that wasn't too late to
go to graduate school.

00:51:53.946 --> 00:51:56.000
And I asked my wife
about a master's degree.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:56.707
She said, sure.

00:51:56.707 --> 00:51:58.040
It's only four of rive quarters.

00:51:58.040 --> 00:52:01.250
And then when I got
into the office,

00:52:01.250 --> 00:52:03.420
everybody else in my
office was getting a PhD.

00:52:03.420 --> 00:52:05.180
So I thought, maybe
I should get a PhD.

00:52:05.180 --> 00:52:09.080
So I decided to do that.

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:12.120
We lived on research assistant
salaries, my wife and two kids

00:52:12.120 --> 00:52:15.630
and I. We were at poverty
level at that time.

00:52:15.630 --> 00:52:18.590
And then the project ended,
and I lost my RA-ship.

00:52:18.590 --> 00:52:22.077
My adviser helped get me a
job at an aerospace company.

00:52:22.077 --> 00:52:22.660
He's aircraft.

00:52:22.660 --> 00:52:25.360
And then it was touch and go
whether I'd ever finish my PhD

00:52:25.360 --> 00:52:29.450
because I was working
20, 30, 40 hours.

00:52:29.450 --> 00:52:30.570
But I did make it.

00:52:30.570 --> 00:52:32.380
I'm an accidental
Berkeley professor.

00:52:32.380 --> 00:52:36.652
My wife grew up right
next door to Berkeley.

00:52:36.652 --> 00:52:39.110
And when I was graduating, on
the interview tour, she says,

00:52:39.110 --> 00:52:41.300
I can't help but think you're
going to end up with Berkeley.

00:52:41.300 --> 00:52:43.020
And I said, look,
Berkeley's up here.

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:44.420
UCLA's down here.

00:52:44.420 --> 00:52:45.110
I'm graduating.

00:52:45.110 --> 00:52:46.360
This is never going to happen.

00:52:46.360 --> 00:52:49.190
But she forced me as
a graduate student

00:52:49.190 --> 00:52:53.260
to call the chairman of the
department at Berkeley computer

00:52:53.260 --> 00:52:55.530
science to find out
about my application.

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:57.130
So I called this guy.

00:52:57.130 --> 00:53:00.100
He said, well, Dave,
you're in the top 10,

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:01.460
but not the top five.

00:53:01.460 --> 00:53:03.826
And at the time, I'm
thinking, that wasn't so bad.

00:53:03.826 --> 00:53:05.950
So it turns out he said
that to anybody who called.

00:53:08.500 --> 00:53:10.742
But then he took my application.

00:53:10.742 --> 00:53:11.950
Yeah, that seems interesting.

00:53:11.950 --> 00:53:14.206
Handed it to somebody
visiting southern California.

00:53:14.206 --> 00:53:15.330
We had a good conversation.

00:53:15.330 --> 00:53:18.360
They invited me back to
interview and got a job offer.

00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:22.557
I barely got tenure.

00:53:22.557 --> 00:53:24.390
The first project, I
already told you about.

00:53:24.390 --> 00:53:25.490
It was way too ambitious.

00:53:25.490 --> 00:53:28.680
I did the sabbatical,
and I did the RISC stuff.

00:53:28.680 --> 00:53:29.507
Tenure wasn't easy.

00:53:29.507 --> 00:53:31.090
I was one of those
guys that was using

00:53:31.090 --> 00:53:33.770
conferences, where the whole
campus used journals but us.

00:53:33.770 --> 00:53:36.347
So I was the Guinea pig
that went through that.

00:53:36.347 --> 00:53:38.180
The RISC stuff was
pretty new, but I got it.

00:53:38.180 --> 00:53:39.700
After that, things got better.

00:53:39.700 --> 00:53:42.390
But I still get papers
rejected by those jerks

00:53:42.390 --> 00:53:44.650
on the programming committee.

00:53:44.650 --> 00:53:45.900
And so what have I learned?

00:53:45.900 --> 00:53:48.710
What works for me?

00:53:48.710 --> 00:53:50.740
For me, it was maximizing
personal happiness

00:53:50.740 --> 00:53:51.810
versus personal wealth.

00:53:51.810 --> 00:53:53.940
That's always been my guideline.

00:53:53.940 --> 00:53:56.380
In this country, you
think wealth is happiness.

00:53:56.380 --> 00:53:59.120
There's unhappy
billionaires in this world.

00:53:59.120 --> 00:54:02.060
They're not the same thing.

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:04.664
Family first, especially
in that kind of a job.

00:54:04.664 --> 00:54:05.830
People ask you to do things.

00:54:05.830 --> 00:54:07.360
Your family can
go down the list.

00:54:07.360 --> 00:54:08.570
I made my family first.

00:54:08.570 --> 00:54:11.770
So I did-- my wife
and I had two sons.

00:54:11.770 --> 00:54:13.460
So I did Indian guides.

00:54:13.460 --> 00:54:14.700
I was the Cub Scout leader.

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:17.030
I was the soccer coach on
their field trips out there.

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:19.409
So when my rebellious
teenage boy grew up,

00:54:19.409 --> 00:54:20.450
ah, you were never there.

00:54:20.450 --> 00:54:24.010
Then I said, Indian
guides, Cub Scouts.

00:54:24.010 --> 00:54:25.010
So I went down the list.

00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:26.350
He said, oh, OK, maybe.

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:30.630
Passion, courage, and optimism.

00:54:30.630 --> 00:54:32.630
You might be able to tell
I'm a passionate guy.

00:54:32.630 --> 00:54:36.100
I have to believe the
thing I'm doing is going

00:54:36.100 --> 00:54:38.010
to possibly change the world.

00:54:38.010 --> 00:54:41.730
My optimism story goes
back to high school.

00:54:41.730 --> 00:54:46.530
I started dating this girl who
was dating older guys who had

00:54:46.530 --> 00:54:48.342
Corvettes and stuff like that.

00:54:48.342 --> 00:54:49.800
Nevertheless, after
a couple dates,

00:54:49.800 --> 00:54:53.240
I asked her if she
would go steady with me,

00:54:53.240 --> 00:54:55.320
as we would say at the time.

00:54:55.320 --> 00:54:56.850
She'd just been
dating older guys

00:54:56.850 --> 00:54:58.360
and didn't now
what to say to me.

00:54:58.360 --> 00:55:00.151
She says, well, I don't
know how to say no.

00:55:00.151 --> 00:55:02.350
So me being an optimist
and a logical person,

00:55:02.350 --> 00:55:03.190
not a no is a yes.

00:55:03.190 --> 00:55:05.710
So I said, great,
and I hugged her.

00:55:05.710 --> 00:55:08.600
And she said, you know, I'll
let this guy down later.

00:55:08.600 --> 00:55:11.640
But we've been
married 48 years now.

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:13.840
So I think that's OK.

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:16.270
And then, yeah, I think
we swing for the fences.

00:55:16.270 --> 00:55:16.770
Right?

00:55:16.770 --> 00:55:18.520
That's that thing.

00:55:18.520 --> 00:55:20.274
Now another thing--
this is a saying

00:55:20.274 --> 00:55:21.940
that a colleague told
me that's actually

00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:23.064
a couple hundred years old.

00:55:23.064 --> 00:55:26.610
Friends come and go,
but enemies accumulate.

00:55:26.610 --> 00:55:30.020
So ironically, the
physical courage

00:55:30.020 --> 00:55:33.810
that comes with wrestling has
to me been intellectual courage.

00:55:33.810 --> 00:55:37.480
So when I was president of ACM,
the person in charge of DARPA

00:55:37.480 --> 00:55:39.590
was cutting back on
academic funding.

00:55:39.590 --> 00:55:41.857
So I decided to take
him on with my friend Ed

00:55:41.857 --> 00:55:42.920
Lazowska in Washington.

00:55:42.920 --> 00:55:45.390
We tried to get people from
other universities to join us.

00:55:45.390 --> 00:55:47.995
But they were afraid this guy
would be vengeful and cut him

00:55:47.995 --> 00:55:49.980
off, I think with good reason.

00:55:49.980 --> 00:55:53.197
So it was just us taking him
on with editorials in "Science

00:55:53.197 --> 00:55:54.030
Magazine" and stuff.

00:55:54.030 --> 00:55:56.380
So this guy was not a fan of us.

00:55:56.380 --> 00:55:59.200
But we hadn't quite realized--
this was unintentional.

00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:02.660
But the other saying is, the
enemy of my enemy is my friend.

00:56:02.660 --> 00:56:05.370
So we made a lot of friends.

00:56:05.370 --> 00:56:07.600
But keep that in mind.

00:56:07.600 --> 00:56:10.180
Winning as a team
versus an individual.

00:56:10.180 --> 00:56:14.720
In my DNA, I believe a
team of average people

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:18.180
can work together
and beat superstars.

00:56:18.180 --> 00:56:21.660
And then I've already quoted
Fred Brooks about that line.

00:56:21.660 --> 00:56:24.000
Seek out honest feedback
and learn from it.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:25.670
It's easy to avoid feedback.

00:56:25.670 --> 00:56:29.410
But that's how you get better.

00:56:29.410 --> 00:56:33.350
The one warning sign I can
pass on from my 40 years,

00:56:33.350 --> 00:56:35.522
always dangerous
is when somebody

00:56:35.522 --> 00:56:37.480
thinks they're the smartest
person in the room.

00:56:37.480 --> 00:56:39.859
There's a person in
my field who thinks

00:56:39.859 --> 00:56:41.400
he's the smartest
person in the room,

00:56:41.400 --> 00:56:42.900
and everybody hates that guy.

00:56:42.900 --> 00:56:44.904
There was a president
of a university who

00:56:44.904 --> 00:56:46.070
thought he was the smartest.

00:56:46.070 --> 00:56:50.040
That person was fired
for doing a lousy job.

00:56:50.040 --> 00:56:52.450
The people who
founded Enron thought

00:56:52.450 --> 00:56:54.200
they were the smartest
people in the room.

00:56:54.200 --> 00:56:55.750
They went to prison.

00:56:55.750 --> 00:56:59.100
And I even have a
relative who thought

00:56:59.100 --> 00:57:00.930
he was the smartest
person in the room,

00:57:00.930 --> 00:57:03.390
and he's a convicted felon.

00:57:03.390 --> 00:57:04.400
So why would that be?

00:57:04.400 --> 00:57:06.150
Why would this person--
they're probably smart.

00:57:06.150 --> 00:57:07.941
And if they think
they're the smartest, why

00:57:07.941 --> 00:57:09.350
would it be such a bad sign?

00:57:09.350 --> 00:57:11.690
I think it's that they don't
want feedback from anybody.

00:57:11.690 --> 00:57:12.930
If you're the smartest
person in the room,

00:57:12.930 --> 00:57:15.350
you don't need to talk to
anybody about your idea.

00:57:15.350 --> 00:57:18.010
So I think-- but
anyways, run away

00:57:18.010 --> 00:57:21.157
if you find somebody like that.

00:57:21.157 --> 00:57:22.240
This thing happened to me.

00:57:22.240 --> 00:57:25.790
It was like God spoke
in my ear one morning.

00:57:25.790 --> 00:57:28.030
And I remember waking up.

00:57:28.030 --> 00:57:30.570
And it's not how many
projects you start.

00:57:30.570 --> 00:57:31.660
It's how many you finish.

00:57:31.660 --> 00:57:33.730
It was like in my
head, like somebody

00:57:33.730 --> 00:57:34.860
was telling me what to do.

00:57:34.860 --> 00:57:37.670
So ever since that,
that's what I've done.

00:57:37.670 --> 00:57:39.960
So what I do is one
big project at a time.

00:57:39.960 --> 00:57:40.710
I do other things.

00:57:40.710 --> 00:57:42.210
But there's one big
thing at a time.

00:57:42.210 --> 00:57:44.440
So when Hennessy and I
were doing our textbook,

00:57:44.440 --> 00:57:46.650
that was the big thing
that I did that year.

00:57:46.650 --> 00:57:49.730
When I was president of
ACM, I took a sabbatical.

00:57:49.730 --> 00:57:51.740
So that was the one big
thing I did that year.

00:57:51.740 --> 00:57:54.530
And so it turns out, if you
do one big thing a year,

00:57:54.530 --> 00:57:57.620
over 30 years, you can
get a lot of things done.

00:57:57.620 --> 00:57:59.540
But a lot of
academics particularly

00:57:59.540 --> 00:58:01.110
will work on 1,000
things at once

00:58:01.110 --> 00:58:03.430
and not finish
very many of them.

00:58:03.430 --> 00:58:08.060
And then have fun.

00:58:08.060 --> 00:58:10.420
To be successful, you
do have to work hard.

00:58:10.420 --> 00:58:14.380
Our long lost colleague
Jim Gray-- even in his 60s,

00:58:14.380 --> 00:58:15.790
he'd do one all nighter a month.

00:58:15.790 --> 00:58:17.539
So you have to work
hard to be successful.

00:58:17.539 --> 00:58:19.675
But you have to have fun.

00:58:19.675 --> 00:58:21.800
As far as we know, you only
get one chance of this.

00:58:21.800 --> 00:58:23.630
And if you get to the end
without having any fun,

00:58:23.630 --> 00:58:25.000
you've wasted a lot
of opportunities.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:26.666
I can put up with a
lot of stuff as long

00:58:26.666 --> 00:58:28.572
as I play soccer every Sunday.

00:58:28.572 --> 00:58:29.530
I can have a good time.

00:58:29.530 --> 00:58:30.980
So that's my advice.

00:58:30.980 --> 00:58:32.550
Thanks very much.

00:58:32.550 --> 00:58:34.100
[APPLAUSE]

